6. JFrog + EKS	Helm charts, Docker images for Kubernetes

Here's a practical guide to run this project on your personal laptop using Minikube (local Kubernetes, simulating EKS) and JFrog Artifactory OSS (free tier).

Prerequisites — Install these first
# 1. Docker (required for everything)
sudo apt-get install docker.io -y
sudo usermod -aG docker $USER && newgrp docker

# 2. kubectl
curl -LO "https://dl.k8s.io/release/$(curl -sL https://dl.k8s.io/release/stable.txt)/bin/linux/amd64/kubectl"
chmod +x kubectl && sudo mv kubectl /usr/local/bin/

# 3. Minikube (local Kubernetes cluster = simulates EKS)
curl -LO https://storage.googleapis.com/minikube/releases/latest/minikube-linux-amd64
sudo install minikube-linux-amd64 /usr/local/bin/minikube

# 4. Helm
curl https://raw.githubusercontent.com/helm/helm/main/scripts/get-helm-3 | bash

Step 1 — Start Local Kubernetes Cluster
minikube start --driver=docker --cpus=4 --memory=6g
minikube status
kubectl get nodes

Step 2 — Deploy JFrog Artifactory via Helm
# Add JFrog Helm repo
helm repo add jfrog https://charts.jfrog.io
helm repo update

# Create namespace
kubectl create namespace jfrog

# Install Artifactory OSS (free, no license needed)
helm install artifactory jfrog/artifactory-oss \
  --namespace jfrog \
  --set artifactory.service.type=NodePort \
  --set postgresql.postgresqlPassword=password123 \
  --set artifactory.persistence.size=5Gi

# Check pods coming up (takes 2-3 min)
kubectl get pods -n jfrog -w

Step 3 — Access JFrog UI
# Get the access URL
minikube service artifactory-artifactory-oss -n jfrog --url

# Open that URL in browser
# Default login: admin / password
# Change password on first login

Step 4 — Create a Docker Repository in JFrog
In the UI:

Administration → Repositories → Add Repository → Local
Type: Docker, Name: my-docker-local
Save

Step 5 — Push a Docker Image to JFrog
# Get minikube IP
JFROG_URL=$(minikube ip)
JFROG_PORT=$(kubectl get svc artifactory-artifactory-oss -n jfrog -o jsonpath='{.spec.ports[0].nodePort}')

# Configure Docker to allow insecure registry
echo '{"insecure-registries": ["'"$JFROG_URL:$JFROG_PORT"'"]}' | sudo tee /etc/docker/daemon.json
sudo systemctl restart docker

# Login to JFrog registry
docker login $JFROG_URL:$JFROG_PORT -u admin -p <your-password>

# Tag and push an image
docker pull nginx:alpine
docker tag nginx:alpine $JFROG_URL:$JFROG_PORT/my-docker-local/nginx:1.0
docker push $JFROG_URL:$JFROG_PORT/my-docker-local/nginx:1.0

Step 6 — Deploy from JFrog Registry using a Helm Chart
Create a simple Helm chart that pulls the image from JFrog:
helm create my-app

Edit my-app/values.yaml:
image:
  repository: <JFROG_URL>:<JFROG_PORT>/my-docker-local/nginx
  tag: "1.0"
  pullPolicy: Always

imagePullSecrets:
  - name: jfrog-secret

Create the pull secret so Kubernetes can authenticate to JFrog:
kubectl create secret docker-registry jfrog-secret \
  --docker-server=$JFROG_URL:$JFROG_PORT \
  --docker-username=admin \
  --docker-password=<your-password> \
  --namespace=default

Deploy:
helm install my-app ./my-app
kubectl get pods
kubectl get svc my-app

Step 7 — Verify End-to-End
# Check pod is running and pulled from JFrog
kubectl describe pod <pod-name> | grep -A5 "Events"
# Should show: Pulling image "JFROG_URL/my-docker-local/nginx:1.0"

# Access the app
minikube service my-app --url

