│  Your laptop │ ─────────────────► │ JFrog Artifactory│
│  (Docker)    │                    │ (Helm-deployed   │
└──────────────┘                    │  on Minikube)    │
                                    └────────┬─────────┘
                                             │ image pull
                                    ┌────────▼─────────┐
                                    │ Kubernetes Pod   │
                                    │ (Minikube = EKS) │
                                    └──────────────────┘

Troubleshooting Tips
Issue	Fix
Pods stuck in Pending	minikube start --memory=8g — needs more RAM
JFrog takes too long	Normal — wait 3-5 min, watch with -w
Docker push fails	Verify insecure-registry config, restart Docker
ImagePullBackOff	Check pull secret name matches values.yaml
This gives you the full JFrog → Helm → Kubernetes workflow locally before taking it to real AWS EKS.


Important: EKS is NOT AWS Free Tier
EKS control plane costs $0.10/hr ($72/month) regardless of free tier. You'll get a bill.

Truly Free AWS Alternative — k3s on EC2
Uses EC2 t2.micro (free tier: 750 hrs/month) + JFrog Cloud free tier.

Step 1 — JFrog Cloud Free Account
Go to jfrog.com/start-free → sign up for free cloud instance.
You'll get a URL like: https://yourname.jfrog.io

Step 2 — Launch EC2 t2.micro
In AWS Console:

EC2 → Launch Instance
AMI: Ubuntu 22.04 LTS (free tier eligible)
Type: t2.micro (free tier)
Security group — open ports: 22 (SSH), 80, 443, 6443, 8080, 30000-32767
Create/download a key pair (.pem file)
Launch

Step 3 — Install k3s (Lightweight Kubernetes)
# SSH into your EC2 instance
ssh -i your-key.pem ubuntu@<EC2-PUBLIC-IP>

# Install k3s (single-node Kubernetes cluster)
curl -sfL https://get.k3s.io | sh -

# Verify
sudo kubectl get nodes

# Set up kubectl for your user
mkdir -p ~/.kube
sudo cp /etc/rancher/k3s/k3s.yaml ~/.kube/config
sudo chown $USER ~/.kube/config
kubectl get nodes

Step 4 — Install Helm
curl https://raw.githubusercontent.com/helm/helm/main/scripts/get-helm-3 | bash
helm version

Step 5 — Push Docker Image to JFrog Cloud
# On your EC2 instance (or local machine with Docker)
docker login yourname.jfrog.io -u <your-email> -p <your-api-key>
# API key: JFrog UI → top-right avatar → Edit Profile → Generate API Key

docker pull nginx:alpine
docker tag nginx:alpine yourname.jfrog.io/default-docker-local/nginx:1.0
docker push yourname.jfrog.io/default-docker-local/nginx:1.0

Step 6 — Create Kubernetes Pull Secret
kubectl create secret docker-registry jfrog-secret \
  --docker-server=yourname.jfrog.io \
  --docker-username=<your-email> \
  --docker-password=<your-api-key>

Step 7 — Deploy via Helm from JFrog
# Add JFrog as Helm repo (for Helm charts stored in JFrog)
helm repo add my-jfrog https://yourname.jfrog.io/artifactory/default-helm \
  --username <your-email> --password <your-api-key>
helm repo update

# OR just use a local chart pointing to JFrog Docker image
helm create my-app

# Edit my-app/values.yaml:
#   image.repository: yourname.jfrog.io/default-docker-local/nginx
#   image.tag: "1.0"
#   imagePullSecrets: [{name: jfrog-secret}]

helm install my-app ./my-app
kubectl get pods
kubectl get svc

